Unilateral Cut by Bush
   In Gains Tax Is Unlikely
But senior administration officials said that
administration lawyers, including the White House legal
counsel, have informally indicated that doing so without
congressional consent would exceed the executive branch's
legal power. As a result, it's extremely unlikely that
President Bush or Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady would
make such a move, the officials said.
   With conservatives increasingly public in their attacks on
the administration, particularly on Mr. Bush's top economic
advisers, the officials were reluctant to go on the record to
give their views.